<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,259,1366]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,467,403,429]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among Brazilian species, recognized by the combination of small size (ca. 
<quantity box="[1320,1424,403,430]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.95" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="1.95">1.95 mm</quantity>
), the grey to black color, the pronotum with very shallow impressions and coarse dense punctuation, the pronotal shape, and the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[499,584,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 36–37" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[163,1429,209,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-28@70.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 36–37. Habitus and male genitalia of holotypes. 36. Hydrochus forcipulus n. sp. 37. Hydrochus forcipuloides n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043322" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043322/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
; described below). Differentiation from other similarly small sized species with similarly shaped pronotum will require dissection of males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,259,1366]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,336,547,573]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Description</emphasis>
. Size: 
<typeStatus box="[411,508,547,573]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">holotype</typeStatus>
(length/width, mm): body (length to elytral apices) 1.95/0.78; head width 0.53; pronotum l/w 0.50/0.49; PA 0.47; PB 0.43; elytra 1.27/0.78. Habitus as illustrated (
<figureCitation box="[1047,1131,583,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 36–37" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[163,1429,209,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-28@70.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 36–37. Habitus and male genitalia of holotypes. 36. Hydrochus forcipulus n. sp. 37. Hydrochus forcipuloides n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043322" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043322/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
). Body size small (ca. 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.36" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="2.36">2.36 mm</quantity>
). Dorsum grey, with moderately strong iridescence, elytra without black spots. Legs brown to testaceous, with tibiofemoral joints darker. Punctation on elytra ca. 1–2x that of pronotum. Elytra interstriae ca. 0.5–1x strial puncture diameter. Interstria 9 
<superScript attach="left" box="[381,394,691,705]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">th</superScript>
more convex than others, overhanging 10 
<superScript attach="left" box="[861,874,691,705]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">th</superScript>
interstria. Usual area of callus on 5 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1268,1281,691,705]" fontSize="6" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">th</superScript>
not raised.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,259,1366]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Pronotum slightly wider than long (as ca. 15/16), widest at anterior margin, markedly narrowed at base, sides very slightly arcuate, smooth; anterior margin bisinuate, with fringe of short setae over lateral 1/3; depressions very shallow; punctation coarse and dense.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,259,1366]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Elytra with spaces between strial punctures narrow ridges to ca. 0.5x their diameter; apices rather sharply conjointly rounded in dorsal view, in lateral view outer margin with slight angulation.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,259,1366]" box="[199,1432,907,934]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Ventral characters: Mentum moderately coarsely punctate, median fovea shallow; submentum without foveae.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,259,1366]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[376,458,943,970]" captionStart="FIGURES 36–37" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[163,1429,209,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-28@70.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 36–37. Habitus and male genitalia of holotypes. 36. Hydrochus forcipulus n. sp. 37. Hydrochus forcipuloides n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043322" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043322/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
) general characters: genitalia very narrow, elongate, length ca. 6x greatest width, parameres longer than basal piece (ratio ca. 19/15); parameres tapering to very fine apices, very narrow and extending well beyond distal end of aedeagus, medial margins beyond aedeagus tip diverging slightly one from the other, plsa absent, in dorsal/ventral views lateral margins of tips straight; in lateral view paramere tip very thin and arcuate ventrad, sharply pointed apically; aedeagus moderately wide, agw at ca. midlength; basal piece in dorsal/ventral views with slightly arcuate lateral margins, in lateral view arcuate, dorsal surface more arcuate than ventral, maximum width in dorsal/ventral views slightly greater than lateral width, orifice asymmetrical, margin sclerotized.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,259,1366]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Dorsal surface: adtl at ca. midlength of aedeagus; pdmm slightly overlapping alm in proximal ½, otherwise approximating alm; adbl small.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,259,1366]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Ventral surface: avtl at ca. midlength of aedeagus; pvmm overlapping alm in proximal 1/3, medial margins very narrowly separated.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,945,1339,1366]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,259,1366]" box="[199,945,1339,1366]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1339,1365]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named in reference to the forceps-like male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
